insert into "books" ("description", "image_url", "page_count", "published_at", "subtitle", "title") values ('Telecommunications regulatory reform has proven itself to be a worthy campaign in search of a sound public policy agenda. The loudest voices of the past decades of arguments over how utility regulation meets the Internet come from such dissimilar points of view that they continue to talk past and around each other. The telecommunications reform machine marches on, much the same today as over a decade ago when the most recent modifications to our nation''s Communications Law were passed under the name of the Telecommunications Act of 1996. Leadership is desperately needed. Unwieldy bureaucracies continue to react to exponentially changing communication technologies rather than line up under a coherent plan to proactively chart success to develop the infrastructure for competition in the global economy. If ever there was a need to keep an eye on the prize, it is now. The prize is an educated democracy with a civic duty and digital skills to compete globally. This thesis explores the path to more effective public policy toward that end.', 'http://books.google.com/books/content?id=JFVMFnXjXHwC&printsec=frontcover&img=1&zoom=1&edge=curl&source=gbs_api', '96', '2008', DEFAULT, 'Defining Social Policy: Should Telecommunications Regulation be Devolved to the States?');
insert into "books" ("description", "image_url", "page_count", "published_at", "subtitle", "title") values ('A good book may have the power to change the way we see the world, but a great book actually becomes part of our daily consciousness, pervading our thinking to the point that we take it for granted, and we forget how provocative and challenging its ideas once were—and still are. The Structure of Scientific Revolutions is that kind of book. When it was first published in 1962, it was a landmark event in the history and philosophy of science. Fifty years later, it still has many lessons to teach. With The Structure of Scientific Revolutions, Kuhn challenged long-standing linear notions of scientific progress, arguing that transformative ideas don’t arise from the day-to-day, gradual process of experimentation and data accumulation but that the revolutions in science, those breakthrough moments that disrupt accepted thinking and offer unanticipated ideas, occur outside of “normal science,” as he called it. Though Kuhn was writing when physics ruled the sciences, his ideas on how scientific revolutions bring order to the anomalies that amass over time in research experiments are still instructive in our biotech age. This new edition of Kuhn’s essential work in the history of science includes an insightful introduction by Ian Hacking, which clarifies terms popularized by Kuhn, including paradigm and incommensurability, and applies Kuhn’s ideas to the science of today. Usefully keyed to the separate sections of the book, Hacking’s introduction provides important background information as well as a contemporary context. Newly designed, with an expanded index, this edition will be eagerly welcomed by the next generation of readers seeking to understand the history of our perspectives on science.', 'http://books.google.com/books/content?id=3eP5Y_OOuzwC&printsec=frontcover&img=1&zoom=1&edge=curl&source=gbs_api', '264', '2012-04-18', '50th Anniversary Edition', 'The Structure of Scientific Revolutions');
