insert into "books" ("description", "image_url", "page_count", "published_at", "subtitle", "title") values ('This study examined self-esteem as a moderator in the relationships between two forms of materialism (vales-based and personality-based) and television, family structure (i.e. whether parents'' relationship was intact), and childhood social status. A sample of college students from a medium-sized university in the Midwest (n =191) completed paper-and-pencil instruments for the variables, and a short demographics form asking age, sex, year in school, ethnicity, and religious affiliation. Results indicated that values-based materialism, as measured by the Material Values Scale (Richins & Dawson, 1992), was only correlated with television viewing (r = .17), and personality-based materialism, as measured by the Belk Materialism Scale (Belk, 1985), was only correlated with self-esteem (r = -.32). Regression analyses were done to examine the potential moderating effects of self-esteem between the aforementioned predictors and both forms of materialism. Results showed that self-esteem moderated only the relationship between television and values-based materialism. However, the relationship was opposite of the hypothesized direction; watching television was predictive of increased values-based materialism for people with high self-esteem, but not for those with low self-esteem. Limitations, suggestions for future research, and implications for counseling psychologists are also discussed.', 'http://books.google.com/books/content?id=DTgZ1rBzFOQC&printsec=frontcover&img=1&zoom=1&edge=curl&source=gbs_api', '99', '2007', DEFAULT, 'Pathways to Materialism: Examining Self-esteem as a Moderator');
