insert into "books" ("description", "image_url", "page_count", "published_at", "subtitle", "title") values ('The new or additional information optimized transmit signal can be made data driven or adaptive leading to adaptive-transmit class radar. Transmit signal can be changed at real-time (or near real-time) to emphasize the least known objects, so that they can be correctly classified as target or clutter.', 'http://books.google.com/books/content?id=z_o81graQ9UC&printsec=frontcover&img=1&zoom=1&edge=curl&source=gbs_api', '117', '2006', DEFAULT, 'An Information Theoretic Approach to Transmit Signal Design for MIMO Radar');
insert into "books" ("description", "image_url", "page_count", "published_at", "subtitle", "title") values ('Transmit beamforming can not only increase performance in wireless MIMO systems, but also add increased performance when put in combination with other MIMO systems like spatial multiplexing and space time codes. TB has advantages over other MIMO schemes because by measuring the channel, one can use adaptive modulation techniques to achieve a coding gain not obtainable without channel state information (CSI). Past research assumed the feedback channel was error free and had no delay. This isolated the effects of finite rate feedback. We assume there is delay in the feedback channel along with imperfect channel estimation (ICE) at the receiver. We will show how detrimental these effects can be to TB''s performance and can not be ignored.', 'http://books.google.com/books/content?id=od4CqVyu4fQC&printsec=frontcover&img=1&zoom=1&edge=curl&source=gbs_api', '72', '2008', DEFAULT, 'Analysis of Transmit Beamforming and Fair OFDMA Scheduling');
insert into "books" ("description", "image_url", "page_count", "published_at", "subtitle", "title") values ('This thesis is devoted to the study of the effects of noisy channel estimation at the receiver and partial CSI at the transmitters on the optimum transmit strategies for Gaussian multi-input multi-output (MIMO) systems. The main focus of the thesis is on achievable rate maximization problems, solutions of which give the optimum resource allocation and channel estimation schemes for single-user and multi-user MIMO systems.', 'http://books.google.com/books/content?id=YB8llmdop0cC&printsec=frontcover&img=1&zoom=1&edge=curl&source=gbs_api', '181', '2008', DEFAULT, 'Optimum Transmit Strategies for Gaussian Multi-user MIMO Systems with Partial CSI and Noisy Channel Estimation');
insert into "books" ("description", "image_url", "page_count", "published_at", "subtitle", "title") values ('During the radio frequency (RF) transmit phase, the increased sample-coil interactions with shortened wavelength at high static fields result in load dependent inhomogeneous transverse magnetic fields (B1 fields), leading to magnetic resonance imaging artifacts. The optimization of non-uniform RF B1 fields at high static fields may be accomplished by the independent current control on each coil element in a transmit array, which requires electrical isolation among mutually coupled transmit array elements. In this work, an RF current source drive and decoupling technique using a high power Metal-Oxide-Semiconductor Field Effect Transistor (MOSFET) is introduced as a method of enhancing current driven into transmit elements and simultaneously suppressing current induced by neighboring elements at 3 tesla. The proposed RF current source is operated in a gated class AB push-pull scheme for optimization of efficiency and linearity. A close approximation to ideal current source operation is demonstrated, where the drive current is shown to be insensitive to a specified loading range. A head sized 2 channel volume transmit array integrating RF current sources shows the capability of B1 field pattern control in a deterministic manner and large flip angle imaging, enabling the practical use of the proposed technique in parallel excitations.', 'http://books.google.com/books/content?id=DA0kwMsTGEMC&printsec=frontcover&img=1&zoom=1&edge=curl&source=gbs_api', '106', '2008', DEFAULT, 'RF Current Source Drive and Decoupling Technique for Parallel Transmit Arrays in Magnetic Resonance Imaging');
